\section{Intersurface mixing}

Figure \ref{fig:S2} displays the band gap ${E_g}$ of a TI slab as a function of ${L_z}$ calculated for $m=0$ and 50meV.
For $m=0$, intersurface mixing creates a finite gap, which exhibits an oscillatory exponential decay with $L_z$ \cite{ref:19,ref:20,ref:21}.
This behavior is approximately described by ${E_g}=2\left|\Delta \right|$ and $\Delta \propto {e^{-\alpha {L_z}}}\operatorname{sin}\beta {L_z}$, where $\alpha = {A_1}/2\sqrt{{B_1}^2-{D_1}^2}$ and $\beta = \sqrt{{B_0}/{B_1}-{\alpha^2}}$.
The oscillation period $\pi /\beta$ is estimated to be 2.5nm for Bi$_2$Se$_3$.
For $m \ne 0$, ${E_g}$ is expressed generally as ${E_g}=2\operatorname{min}\left|{\Delta \pm m}\right|$.
For ${L_z}\geqslant5{\text{nm}}$ and $m=50{\text{meV}}$, $\left|\Delta\right|$ is orders of magnitudes smaller than $m$ and hence ${E_g}\cong2\left|{m}\right|$.
Thus, the QAH criterion $\left|{m}\right|>\left|\Delta\right|$ \cite{ref:2,ref:3,ref:21} is reasonably fulfilled under these conditions.
